# mocc — mock OIDC provider for agents

This instance is running at `{{.BaseURL}}`. It accepts **any** `client_id` and `client_secret`, so agents do not need credentials — they only need a test user email.

## 1. Health check

```bash
curl -sf {{.BaseURL}}/.well-known/openid-configuration >/dev/null && echo "up" || echo "down"
```

## 2. Test users (live from this instance's users.yaml)

{{if eq (len .Users) 0 -}}
*No users configured on this instance.*
{{- else -}}
| Email | Name | Claims |
|-------|------|--------|
{{range .Users}}| `{{.Email}}` | {{.Name}} | {{formatClaims .Claims}} |
{{end}}
{{- end}}

If you need a custom user or custom claims, edit `users.yaml` and restart mocc, or pass override claims in the direct-mint request body (see below).

## 3. Get a token — the fast way (direct mint)

Best for agents: skip the browser flow and mint a signed JWT directly.

```bash
curl -sX GET "{{.BaseURL}}/token/{{.ExampleEmail}}" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"aud":"my-client-id"}'
```

Response contains `token` (the signed RS256 JWT) and `claims` (decoded payload).

Extract just the token:

```bash
TOKEN=$(curl -sX GET "{{.BaseURL}}/token/{{.ExampleEmail}}" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"aud":"my-client-id"}' | jq -r .token)

curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" http://your-api/whoami
```

Override or add claims by including them in the JSON body:

```bash
curl -sX GET "{{.BaseURL}}/token/{{.ExampleEmail}}" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
        "aud": "my-client-id",
        "roles": ["viewer"],
        "custom": {"featureFlags": ["alpha"]}
      }'
```

## 4. Get a token — the full authorization code flow (with PKCE)

Use this when you are testing an actual OIDC client integration rather than the token itself.

1. Generate a PKCE verifier/challenge:

   ```bash
   VERIFIER=$(openssl rand -base64 64 | tr -d '=+/' | cut -c1-64)
   CHALLENGE=$(printf '%s' "$VERIFIER" | openssl dgst -sha256 -binary | openssl base64 | tr -d '=' | tr '/+' '_-')
   ```

2. Send the user to `/authorize`:

   ```
   GET {{.BaseURL}}/authorize
     ?response_type=code
     &client_id=any-client-id
     &redirect_uri=http://localhost:5173/api/callback
     &scope=openid+profile+email
     &state=<state>
     &code_challenge=<CHALLENGE>
     &code_challenge_method=S256
   ```

   The user picks a test user on mocc's login page. mocc redirects to `redirect_uri` with `?code=...&state=...`.

3. Exchange the code for tokens:

   ```bash
   curl -sX POST {{.BaseURL}}/token \
     -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
     -d "grant_type=authorization_code&code=$CODE&client_id=any-client-id&redirect_uri=http://localhost:5173/api/callback&code_verifier=$VERIFIER"
   ```

## 5. Verifying tokens

- Issuer: `{{.BaseURL}}`
- Discovery: `{{.BaseURL}}/.well-known/openid-configuration`
- JWKS: `{{.BaseURL}}/jwks.json`
- Algorithm: `RS256`

Any OIDC client library pointed at the issuer above will discover the rest automatically.

## 6. Endpoint cheat sheet

| Endpoint | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| `GET /.well-known/openid-configuration` | Discovery document |
| `GET /jwks.json` | Public signing keys |
| `GET /authorize` | Start auth code flow (interactive) |
| `POST /token` | Exchange code for tokens |
| `GET /token/{email}` | Direct-mint a token for an existing user (agent-friendly) |
| `GET /userinfo` | OIDC userinfo endpoint |
| `GET /SKILL.md` | This document (dynamically generated) |

## 7. Gotchas

- `client_id` and `client_secret` are **not validated** — any value is accepted. Do not rely on mocc to reject bad clients.
- Tokens are short-lived. Mint a new one rather than refreshing.
- `GET /token/{email}` requires the email to exist in this instance's users.yaml. A 404 means you need to add the user or pick one from the table above.
- Do not deploy this anywhere real. It is a mock.
